Wow, that's really
awesome to see.

00:05:10.570 --> 00:05:14.645
Oh man, look at that
it just [WHISTLE].

00:05:14.645 --> 00:05:15.145
Yes!

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:22.782
Once the balloon is in the air,
we're actively tracking it.

00:05:22.782 --> 00:05:23.990
We have two devices in there.

00:05:23.990 --> 00:05:25.830
They're both sending
us GPS location.

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:26.590
So they're close.

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:28.131
They're a little
off from each other,

00:05:28.131 --> 00:05:30.350
but you can see she's
drifting southeast, ever

00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:32.390
so slightly, which is
exactly what we expected.

00:05:35.530 --> 00:05:37.710
We do lose contact
with the balloon

00:05:37.710 --> 00:05:40.780
at about 20,000 feet, when
it leaves cell reception.

00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:43.290
The cell phone is still
getting GPS data up

00:05:43.290 --> 00:05:46.980
to about 60,000 feet, when
it then loses GPS data.

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:49.480
When the balloon
rises, it expands.

00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:52.270
And when it gets high
enough, it bursts.

00:05:52.270 --> 00:05:54.080
And that's when the
parachute deploys,

00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:56.220
and it starts to
descend back to earth.

00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:58.720
At this point, it's falling at
about five meters per second,

00:05:58.720 --> 00:05:59.890
with a parachute.

00:05:59.890 --> 00:06:01.360
And it's spinning around.

00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:04.960
So it takes it a while to get a
cell reception and a GPS lock,

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:06.920
once it gets below there.

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:10.020
It could land on a
freeway, which we hope not.

00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:12.870
It could land in a farm field,
or it could land in the water.

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:13.744
We don't know.

00:06:13.744 --> 00:06:15.410
VIMAL BHALODIA: The
worst possible thing

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:17.820
that could go wrong is
that the payload actually

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:20.750
lands on a road or
inside a crowded area.

00:06:20.750 --> 00:06:24.530
And we take a lot of precautions
in choosing both our launch

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:26.270
site as well as our
expected landing site

00:06:26.270 --> 00:06:28.146
to make sure that that's
not going to happen.

00:06:28.146 --> 00:06:30.645
HEATHER BRUNDAGE: We could just
lose the balloon completely.

00:06:30.645 --> 00:06:31.780
Have no contact with it.

00:06:31.780 --> 00:06:33.210
The batteries could die.

00:06:33.210 --> 00:06:35.370
The phone could stop working.

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:37.370
The program could
crash and not reboot.

00:06:37.370 --> 00:06:40.146
And if we don't hear from it,
we're not going to get it back.

00:06:40.146 --> 00:06:41.770
VIMAL BHALODIA: About
half the launches

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:43.660
that people have done
and blogged about,

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:47.150
they never saw again.

00:06:47.150 --> 00:06:48.873
HEATHER BRUNDAGE: Hey,
to a great launch.

